          "title": "The incomparable one — praised by her rivals (6:8-9)",
          "body": "Verses 8-9 form the chapter's theological center of gravity. The beloved enumerates the harem with careful arithmetic: sixty queens, eighty concubines, maidens without number. This is not mere boasting of possessions; it is the setup for the 'but' (*aval*) that follows. Amid every category of royal female companionship, the Shulammite stands as *echad* — one, singular, unique. The word appears twice in one verse ('my perfect one is unique; she is her mother's only daughter'), stressing singularity from two angles: in the beloved's eyes, and in her mother's house. What makes this passage theologically remarkable is what happens next: the very queens and concubines who represent the alternative to her exclusive relationship become her most vocal admirers. 'The maidens saw her and called her blessed, the queens and the concubines also, and they praised her' (6:9). The verb *halal* (to praise) is the root of 'hallelujah' — the same word used for the highest praise of God. Even rivals cannot withhold it. The canonical-theological implication for allegorical reading is significant: the church's beauty in Christ is not self-proclaimed but acknowledged by those who stand outside — a witness that transcends internal self-congratulation. For the literal reading, the social psychology is equally profound: genuine, exclusive love so transforms its object that even those who might begrudge it end up conferring it."
