          "body": "Verse 11 opens with what appears to be a purposeful, controlled visit: the bride (or possibly the lover — the speaker is contested) goes down to the nut-tree orchard to observe the springtime blossoming. The vocabulary of verse 11 is entirely agricultural and intentional: she wants to see the valley blossoms, the budding vine, the blooming pomegranates. But verse 12 shatters the controlled frame entirely: 'Before I was aware, my soul set me over the chariots of my noble people.' The verse is one of the most textually difficult in the entire Old Testament — the Hebrew is compressed to the point of near-opacity, and commentators have proposed radically different translations. What is clear is the structural pattern: purposeful descent (v.11) followed by involuntary, exhilarating transport (v.12). The soul acted before the mind could prepare. This is the Song's most direct statement about love's capacity to overwhelm self-consciousness: you go to see the garden, and before you know it, you are among the royal chariots. The chariot (*merkavah*) is the vehicle of highest dignity and speed in the ancient world — to be set 'among the royal chariots' is to find oneself suddenly in a sphere of grandeur and velocity you did not choose. The pastoral and allegorical readings converge here: genuine love of the right kind sweeps the self into something larger than itself."
