          "body": "The chapter closes with a call-and-response that is simultaneously an invitation and a deflection. The Daughters cry four times: 'Come back, come back, O Shulammite; come back, come back, that we may gaze at you!' (6:13). The fourfold repetition ('come back' — *shuvi*, imperative feminine) is the Song's most urgent invitation, combining admiration and desire to see. The bride's counter-question ('Why should you gaze at the Shulammite, as at the dance of the two companies?') introduces the book's only use of the title 'Shulammite' — a term appearing nowhere else in the Hebrew Bible. Whether it means 'woman of Shulem/Shunem' (a geographic designation) or the feminine of 'Solomon' (the peace-woman, Solomon's counterpart) remains debated. What is unambiguous is the bride's rhetorical resistance to the public gaze: why should you gaze at me? The comparison to 'the dance of Mahanaim' — the two camps — is equally debated: a celebratory victory dance before two assembled audiences? A sacred processional dance? Whatever the specific referent, the image is one of spectacle, a dance so extraordinary that crowds form on both sides to watch. The chapter that opened with anxious searching ends with a call to a woman so beautiful that watching her move is its own event. The chapter does not resolve cleanly — it ends in question form, sustaining the tension between the lover's exclusive gaze and the world's desire to participate in that beauty."
